Architecture plan for Issue #49: Apply colorful gradient background to the built frontend

Current project shape
- Backend: Rust Axum API in `backend/` with workspace configuration in root `Cargo.toml`.
- Frontend: React + Vite + TypeScript SPA in `frontend/`.
- Styling: Tailwind-backed global CSS in `frontend/src/styles.css`, with app composition in `frontend/src/App.tsx` and bootstrapping in `frontend/src/main.tsx`.
- Tests: Playwright E2E specs in `e2e/`; root npm scripts drive frontend build/lint and Rust checks.

Module structure and file organization
- Keep the gradient implementation in the frontend only.
- Define shared background/theme tokens at the global stylesheet level (`frontend/src/styles.css`) rather than duplicating gradients in individual components.
- Use CSS custom properties for:
  - global colorful app gradient
  - dark-mode muted colorful app gradient
  - neutral elevated surfaces used over the gradient
  - borders/shadows needed for legibility
- Apply the global gradient to `html`, `body`, and the React root/full-page wrapper so every route inherits the same background.
- Update full-page containers in `frontend/src/App.tsx` so app frame, auth gate/loading wrapper, and login page do not use opaque neutral canvas backgrounds that hide the global gradient.
- Preserve near-neutral panels/cards for mailbox sidebar, message list, reading pane, compose panel, and login card so text remains readable.

Shared types and contracts
- No backend API or shared DTO changes are needed.
- No database, auth, mail, or routing contract changes are needed.
- Styling tokens are the only new shared contract: frontend components should reference the global CSS variables/Tailwind-compatible utility classes rather than hard-coded page backgrounds.

Dependencies between issues
- Issue #49 depends on the existing frontend design system and app shell.
- There are no other open implementation issues in this session, so it can be completed independently.
- Because the gradient is global, changes should be verified across authenticated shell, login/auth gate states, and dark mode.

Key design decisions
- Implement the colorful background as a restrained multi-stop gradient to satisfy the request without making the quiet-mail UI visually noisy.
- Use a softer/muted gradient for dark mode to avoid high-contrast color bloom behind dark surfaces.
- Keep content surfaces translucent or near-neutral with sufficient contrast; do not make message/card surfaces fully transparent.
- Prefer global tokens and minimal component edits over broad markup rewrites, reducing regression risk.
- Verification should include `npm --workspace frontend run build` and, if practical, frontend lint/check scripts.
